                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Depending on the situation I use a few different timers.
<br />

<br />
Xp-group situation,low yield (1-3 adds), low danger element: Intuition
<br />
As someone coined before me, "eyeballing it". Rarely have to time it.
<br />

<br />
Xp-group situation, high yield (4-6 adds), low-medium danger element: Mana regen %.
<br />

<br />
I'll actually use regeneration tics to time mezzes, either by hitting the "sweet spot" (Ie: regenning enough to cast the next mez indefinately) or by timing tic % increases and doing a pattern (mez at +5%, mez at +10%, mez at 0% net loss, etc). Honestly rarely use this, but it does come up. 
<br />

<br />
Raid-situation, low yield (1-4 adds), low-danger element, short-term: Intuition, mez-refresh timer. 
<br />
I would classify Xegony or Saryrn as this. Mez-refresh timer just means when rapture pops for re-use (emp specifically).
<br />

<br />
Raid-situation, high yield (5-20 adds), medium-high danger element, short-term: Intuition.
<br />
I would classify the add-shitter PoE dust ring as this as an example, or perhaps Bertoxxulous. Generally these cases are too chaotic to keep a timer beyond bliss's refresh timer.
<br />

<br />
Raid-situation, high yield (5-20 adds), high danger element, long-term: Stopwatch, 30-1-minute interval depending on severity of a break should it happen. 
<br />
Rathe. PoAir dust ring. Generally involving long periods of mezzing. Side note: I despise these. Generally these are the one-fuckup-you-die type CC encounters that take ages to win.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
	<tr>
